{
  "id": "019d2eb3-8e59-7b70-8ae0-ee1f713271c1",
  "content": "## Access Tracking in Retrieval Path (Issue #16)\n\nImplemented access tracking that records `last_accessed` and `access_count` when entries are returned via the retrieval pipeline. Key design decisions:\n\n### Architecture\n- `record_access(entry_ids)` added to `QueryableStore` trait\n- LiteStore: batched Redb write transaction, all entries updated atomically\n- PostgresStore: `UPDATE ... WHERE id = ANY($1)` for efficient batched update\n- Retriever calls `spawn_access_recording()` (fire-and-forget via `tokio::spawn`) after final result assembly\n\n### Intentional Design Choices\n- **Ephemeral metadata**: Access counts are Redb-only in LiteStore — NOT persisted to knowledge JSON files. This is intentional: access tracking is operational telemetry, not source-of-truth data. Counts reset on `rebuild_from_files`.\n- **Non-blocking**: Write happens after results are assembled and returned. Uses `tokio::spawn` so search latency is unaffected.\n- **Graceful failure**: All errors are logged as `warn!()` and swallowed. Access tracking is optimization, not correctness.\n- **Tier 1 only**: Only entries in the final result set (after RBAC, visibility, metadata filtering) are tracked. Intermediate candidates are not.\n\n### Known Limitations (deferred)\n- Sync Redb I/O runs on async runtime (pre-existing pattern across all LiteStore methods)\n- Full entry serde round-trip for 2-field update (could be optimized with separate access stats table)\n- No backpressure on spawned tasks (acceptable for current scale)",
  "source_version": "mcp",
